1. Always generate code in english

2. Follow NestJS naming conventions:

   - Controllers: suffix with .controller.ts
   - Services: suffix with .service.ts
   - Modules: suffix with .module.ts
   - DTOs: suffix with .dto.ts
   - Entities: suffix with .entity.ts
   - Interfaces: suffix with .interface.ts
   - Errors: suffix with .errors.ts
   - Exception Filters: suffix with .exception.filter.ts
   - Interceptors: suffix with .interceptor.ts

3. File structure rules:

   - One class per file
   - Keep related files in feature modules
   - Use barrel (index.ts) exports
   - Group by feature, not by type
   - Organize domain-specific code in its own module (e.g., wallet, user, p2p-order)
   - Keep core functionality in core/ directory

4. Code style rules:

   - Use TypeScript decorators consistently
   - Implement proper dependency injection
   - Use async/await over raw promises
   - Use proper types, avoid 'any'
   - Use interfaces for data transfer objects
   - Handle BigInt conversions through interceptors
   - Use enums for fixed value sets

5. API endpoint rules:

   - Use proper HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
   - Follow REST naming conventions
   - Use DTOs for request/response validation
   - Wrap responses in a standard format using interceptors
   - Use proper HTTP status codes for errors

6. Error handling rules:

   - Use built-in exception filters
   - Create domain-specific error classes
   - Implement custom exception filters per domain
   - Map domain errors to appropriate HTTP status codes
   - Use descriptive error messages
   - Handle async errors properly

7. Documentation rules:

   - Use OpenAPI/Swagger decorators
   - Document all public APIs
   - Include example requests/responses
   - Document error responses
   - Include TODO comments for future improvements

8. Domain-specific rules:
   - Implement token standards interfaces (ERC20, ICRC)
   - Use proper error handling for blockchain operations
   - Validate blockchain-specific data types
   - Handle numeric precision for financial operations
